REGULARIZED LINEAR REGRESSION

set.seed(577)
YY = as.numeric(elec_data[,1]); YY = YY - mean(YY)  # center the response
XX = as.matrix(elec_data[,-1]); XX = scale(XX,center=T,scale=T) # center the predictors
n = nrow(XX)

lam = 1

set.seed(577)
train_index = sample(1:n,n*0.7,replace = FALSE)
X = XX[train_index,]  # trainining X
Y = YY[train_index]  # training Y
X_test = XX[-c(train_index),] # Test X
Y_test = YY[-c(train_index)] # Test Y

thing = seq(0,1,.1)

for (i in thing){
cv = glmnet(x=X, y=Y, family="gaussian",alpha=i)
min1 = cv$lambda.min
train1 = predict(cv, newx = X, s=min1)
test1 = predict(cv, newx= X_test, s = min1)
trainMSE = mean((Y - train1)^2)
testMSE = mean((Y_test - test1)^2)
trandts = cbind(trainMSE, testMSE)
print(trandts)
}

GRADIANT BOOSTING

set.seed(577)
train = sample(1:nrow(elec_data), 5000, replace=FALSE)
elec_train = elec_data[train,]
elec_test = elec_data[-train,]
y_test = elec_data$Usage[-train]
y_train = elec_data$Usage[train]

elec_gbm = gbm(Usage~.,data= elec_train, distribution = "gaussian", 
               n.trees=5000, interaction.depth = 4, cv.folds = 0)
summary.gbm(elec_gbm)
plot(elec_gbm, "mean")

gbm.perf(elec_gbm, plot.it=TRUE,
         oobag.curve = FALSE, overlay=TRUE, method="OOB")

NEURAL NET

train.index = sample(1:nrow(elec_data),5000)

std.data = as.data.frame(scale(elec_data, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE))
std.train = std.data[train.index,]
std.test = std.data[-train.index,]

MSE.trnnet = matrix(0,6,1)
MSE.tsnnet = matrix(0,6,1)
for (i in 1:6){
nnet.fit = nnet(Usage~., data = std.data, subset = train.index, size = i, rang = 0.1,
              decay = 5e-4, maxit = 200)

predtr.nnet = predict(nnet.fit,newdata=std.train,type="raw")
predts.nnet = predict(nnet.fit,newdata=std.test,type="raw")
std.train.usage = (std.train$Usage)
std.test.usage = (std.test$Usage)

MSE.trnnet[i] = mean((std.train.usage - predtr.nnet)^2)
MSE.tsnnet[i] = mean((std.test.usage - predts.nnet)^2)

}
MSE.nnet = cbind(MSE.trnnet, MSE.tsnnet)
colnames(MSE.nnet) = c("Train", "Test")
rownames(MSE.nnet) = c("Node 1","Node 2","Node 3","Node 4","Node 5","Node 6")

QUESTION

Of all the choices above, the most compelling choice for model selection is neural net, becuase it usually gives the best predictive performance. However,the other models performed relatively similiar so they could also be good choices. Since all of the other models perform relatively the same, there does not seam to be much benefit from chosing one model over the other. However, when it comes to simplicity, maybe doing a Lasso regression would be better because it shrinks unwanted values to 0. Doing an linear regression also showed the lowest values, so something simple like that would work.
